properties.field.notes: This stand of at least a dozen trees is along Tilley Rd in Millerslyvania State Park. While the road basically bisect the State Park, this group of trees is a bit exposed given the creeks culvert it sits next to. There is quite a bit of standing water around the stand at the moment. I suspect it drys up middle to late summer. At least 8 trees were completely dead. Another 2 or 3 had thinning foliage throughout. There were also 3 that had been cut down at some point which you can see in the photos. Might have been cut due to their proximity to the power lines.

properties.field.notes: Two trees appear to have expanded into each other at ground level. This observation is about the trunk on the right in photos with both trunks. They are within a few feet of another, separate Western Redcedar, which is also reported in the Western Redcedar Dieback Map: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/134931662. The tops of all three trees show in the overall canopy photo; this observation is about the one in the center of that photo. Tree does not show any tip dieback. It appears to have normal dieback of interior shaded branches, shown in one photo. There is also one small branch in the canopy with dead leaves shown in a canopy photo; it is probably from something breaking it, not dieback from stress.

properties.field.notes: This tree (as shown) was cut back for the sake of the path beneath its canopy. Otherwise, it appears to be fairly healthy. It is growing up a slope from a stream that flows with at least a trickle of water year round. There is little visible damage on this tree besides the trimming for the trail. As for other species' health, this forest is fairly healthy. There are very few dead snags besides those that have fallen in the recent windstorms we've been experiencing. However, I do believe that this forest could be at risk in the future due to the abundance of invasive himalayan blackberry and english ivy, which have choked out some native wildflower species. The ivy has started to climb nearby bigleaf maples, red alders, and douglas firs and should be removed to prevent harm to these trees.
